## Part D: Reflection

### Model Comparison
The fine-tuned models provided more task-relevant outputs compared to the generic model. The generic model focused on sentiment (positive/negative), which is not directly aligned with fraud detection. In contrast, the fine-tuned models were better suited for identifying suspicious or spam-like behavior.

### Strengths
- Automation eliminates manual classification
- Ability to process multiple inputs efficiently
- Integration of multiple models improves analysis

### Limitations
- Some models produced similar outputs across different inputs
- Generic model lacks domain-specific understanding
- Accuracy depends heavily on input phrasing

### Improvements
- Use a domain-specific fraud detection model
- Add more diverse and realistic input data
- Implement threshold-based decision logic for better classification

### Real-World Application
This workflow can be used in financial systems to automatically flag suspicious transactions or messages, helping analysts prioritize high-risk cases and reduce manual workload.
